result.text:
A brighter future for #fintechs in 2024? 🤔
 
They’ve had a rough ride, but there seems to be light at the end of the tunnel.
 
At the start of the year, the outlook for #fintech companies was gloomy: Rising interest rates, skyrocketing inflation, fresh cryptocurrency regulations, the Sam Bankman-Fried scandal and the collapse of Silicon Valley Bank made it tough for startups to raise capital.
 
According to @KPMG, overall global funding activity for fintechs - including VC, private equity, and M&A - fell to $17.9 billion in Q2 2023 (from $34.5 billion in Q1 2023 and down from its peak of $103.2 billion at the start of 2022). 
 
But heading into 2024, the outlook isn’t nearly as dire as many had predicted:
 
📈 The market’s new normal has spurred a great deal of re-positioning and innovation
 
📈 Fintech companies able to incorporate generative #AI into their products and partnering with established financial institutions will be successful
 
At @WebSummit in Lisbon this week, my panel said:
 
💬 Meeri Savolainen, CEO, @inzmoapp: “We will see a war for talent.”

💬 @- Rodolphe A., Founder & CEO, @Spendesk: “We are extremely bullish on the fintech space. It’s still the heydays for fintech.”

💬 Samir El-Sabini, Co-Founder & CEO, @GetJuni: “We will see consolidation between fintech but also real competition.”
 
💡 Takeaway: Those fintechs built on solid fundamentals will weather the storm just fine and have plenty of reasons to be optimistic in 2024.
 
#WebSummit #WebSummit2023 #technology #business #martinastravels
